<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>Possible candidates for Sodom or Gomorrah are the sites discovered or visited by [[Walter E. Rast]] and [[R. Thomas Schaub]] in 1973, including [[Bab edh-Dhra]], which was originally excavated in 1965 by archaeologist Paul Lapp, only to have his work continued by Rast and Schaub, following his death due to accidental drowning, in the waters off Cyprus in 1970. Other possibilities also include [[Numeira]], [[al-Safi]], [[Feifa]] and [[Khanazir]], which were also visited by Schaub and Rast. All sites were located near the [[Dead Sea]], with evidence of burning and traces of [[sulfur]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.aish.com/societyWork/sciencenature/Biblical_Archeology_Sodom_and_Gomorrah.asp | title = Does Archeological Data Support the Biblical Story?}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FwTVFk1HK3Y&amp;feature=related |title=The Physical Ashen Remains of Sodom &amp; Gomorrah |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-04-25}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} However, according to Schaub, who dug at Bab edh-Dhra, Numeira was destroyed (2600 BC) at a different time period from Bab edh-Dhra (2350–2067 BC).&lt;ref&gt;Eric H. Cline, ''From Eden to Exile: Unraveling Mysteries of the Bible'' (Tampa, FL: National Geographic, 2007), 60.&lt;/ref&gt; Archaeological remains excavated from Bab edh-Dhra are currently displayed in [[Karak Archaeological Museum]] (Karak Castle), [[Amman Citadel]] Museum, and the [[British Museum]].</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>Possible candidates for Sodom or Gomorrah are the sites discovered or visited by [[Walter E. Rast]] and [[R. Thomas Schaub]] in 1973, including [[Bab edh-Dhra]], which was originally excavated in 1965 by archaeologist Paul Lapp, only to have his work continued by Rast and Schaub, following his death due to accidental drowning, in the waters off Cyprus in 1970. Other possibilities also include [[Numeira]], [[al-Safi]], [[Feifa]] and [[Khanazir]], which were also visited by Schaub and Rast. All sites were located near the [[Dead Sea]], with evidence of burning and traces of [[sulfur]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.aish.com/societyWork/sciencenature/Biblical_Archeology_Sodom_and_Gomorrah.asp | title = Does Archeological Data Support the Biblical Story?}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FwTVFk1HK3Y&amp;feature=related |title=The Physical Ashen Remains of Sodom &amp; Gomorrah |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-04-25}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} However, according to Schaub, who dug at Bab edh-Dhra, Numeira was destroyed (2600 BC) at a different time period from Bab edh-Dhra (2350–2067 BC).&lt;ref&gt;Eric H. Cline, ''From Eden to Exile: Unraveling Mysteries of the Bible'' (Tampa, FL: National Geographic, 2007), 60.&lt;/ref&gt; Archaeological remains excavated from Bab edh-Dhra are currently displayed in [[Karak Archaeological Museum]] (Karak Castle), [[Amman Citadel]] Museum, and the [[British Museum]].</div></td>
</tr>
