<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">−</td>
  <td class="diff-deletedline"><div>Another possible candidate for Sodom is the [[Tell el Hammeh]] dig site which began in 2006 under the direction of [[Steven Collins (archaeologist)|Steven Collins]]. Tell el Hammeh is located in the southern Jordan river valley approximately 14 kilometers Northeast of the Dead Sea, and seemingly fits the Biblical descriptions of the lands of Sodom.&lt;ref&gt;Collins, Steven, and Latayne C. Scott. ''Discovering the City of Sodom: The Fascinating, True Account of the Discovery of the Old Testament’s Most Infamous City.'' New York, N.Y.: [[Simon &amp; Schuster]], 2013. ISBN 978-1451684308&lt;/ref&gt; The ongoing dig is a result of joint cooperation between [[Trinity Southwest University]] and the Department of Antiquities of the [[Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.tallelhammam.com |title=tallelhammam.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} The site is 36 hectares, while the footprint size of general settlement extends beyond this—well over 40 hectares. This size puts Tall el-Hammam as one of the largest [[Middle Bronze Age]] sites that has been discovered in Jordan. Analysis of the findings indicates that the site was occupied from the [[Chalcolithic]] period on up to the [[Iron Age]] (however there may likely be period gaps as well (i.e., Late Bronze Period is missing), along with evidences of glazed artifacts—such as pottery and rocks, and destruction).&lt;ref&gt;Collins, Steven, Khalil Hamdan, and Gary A. Byers. "[http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/TeHEP_ADAJ_2009.pdf Tall al-Hammam: Preliminary Report on Four Seasons of Excavation (2006-2009).]" (PDF) ''Annual of the Department of Antiquities of Jordan'' 53 (2009): 385–414.&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} The researchers claim to have discovered an ash layer containing human bone fragments, which they believe indicates a <del class="diffchange diffchange-inline">[[Chelyabinsk meteor|</del>cataclysmic and sudden end<del class="diffchange diffchange-inline">]]</del> to the civilization in this area. Recently, [[Libyan desert glass|desert glass]] had been found among the glazed pottery shards. [[Desert glass]] requires extremely high temperatures to fuse sand into glass. These temperatures are not found from oil fires, gas fires, or siege fires. It is also evident that the area was not occupied for several centuries afterward. In addition there is evidence of Hellenistic, Eastern Roman, and Byzantine occupation&lt;ref&gt;Graves, David E., and Scott Stripling. "Re-Examination of the Location for the Ancient City of Livias." ''Levant'' 43, no. 2 (2011): 178–200.&lt;/ref&gt; on the site.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/TeHEP_SEASON_FIVE_2010_REPORT.pdf |format=PDF |title=TeHEP Season Five 2010 Report |publisher=tallelhammam.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last=Bolen |first=Todd |title=Arguments Against Locating Sodom at Tall el-Hammam |publisher=[[Biblical Archaeology Society]] |date=2013-02-27 |url= http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/biblical-sites-places/biblical-archaeology-sites/arguments-against-locating-sodom-at-tall-el-hammam/ |accessdate=3 July 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Professor [[Eugene H. Merrill (academic)|Eugene H. Merrill]] believes that the identification of Tall el-Hammeh with Sodom would require an unacceptable restructuring of the biblical chronology.&lt;ref&gt;Merrill, Eugene H. "Texts, Talls, and Old Testament Chronology: Tall Hammam as a Case Study." ''Artifax'' 27, no. 4 (2012): 20–21.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last=Bolen |first=Todd |title=Arguments Against Locating Sodom at Tall el-Hammam |url= http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/biblical-sites-places/biblical-archaeology-sites/arguments-against-locating-sodom-at-tall-el-hammam/ |publisher=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=3 July 2013 |date=2013-02-27}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Contra Collins, Steven. "[http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/BRB-2013-1-Collins_Answers_Merrill.pdf Tall el-Hammam Is Still Sodom: Critical Data-Sets Cast Serious Doubt on E. H. Merrill’s Chronological Analysis.]" (PDF) ''Biblical Research Bulletin'' 13, no. 1 (2013): 1–31.&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">+</td>
  <td class="diff-addedline"><div>Another possible candidate for Sodom is the [[Tell el Hammeh]] dig site which began in 2006 under the direction of [[Steven Collins (archaeologist)|Steven Collins]]. Tell el Hammeh is located in the southern Jordan river valley approximately 14 kilometers Northeast of the Dead Sea, and seemingly fits the Biblical descriptions of the lands of Sodom.&lt;ref&gt;Collins, Steven, and Latayne C. Scott. ''Discovering the City of Sodom: The Fascinating, True Account of the Discovery of the Old Testament’s Most Infamous City.'' New York, N.Y.: [[Simon &amp; Schuster]], 2013. ISBN 978-1451684308&lt;/ref&gt; The ongoing dig is a result of joint cooperation between [[Trinity Southwest University]] and the Department of Antiquities of the [[Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.tallelhammam.com |title=tallelhammam.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} The site is 36 hectares, while the footprint size of general settlement extends beyond this—well over 40 hectares. This size puts Tall el-Hammam as one of the largest [[Middle Bronze Age]] sites that has been discovered in Jordan. Analysis of the findings indicates that the site was occupied from the [[Chalcolithic]] period on up to the [[Iron Age]] (however there may likely be period gaps as well (i.e., Late Bronze Period is missing), along with evidences of glazed artifacts—such as pottery and rocks, and destruction).&lt;ref&gt;Collins, Steven, Khalil Hamdan, and Gary A. Byers. "[http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/TeHEP_ADAJ_2009.pdf Tall al-Hammam: Preliminary Report on Four Seasons of Excavation (2006-2009).]" (PDF) ''Annual of the Department of Antiquities of Jordan'' 53 (2009): 385–414.&lt;/ref&gt;{{better source|date=November 2014}} The researchers claim to have discovered an ash layer containing human bone fragments, which they believe indicates a cataclysmic and sudden end to the civilization in this area. Recently, [[Libyan desert glass|desert glass]] had been found among the glazed pottery shards. [[Desert glass]] requires extremely high temperatures to fuse sand into glass. These temperatures are not found from oil fires, gas fires, or siege fires. It is also evident that the area was not occupied for several centuries afterward. In addition there is evidence of Hellenistic, Eastern Roman, and Byzantine occupation&lt;ref&gt;Graves, David E., and Scott Stripling. "Re-Examination of the Location for the Ancient City of Livias." ''Levant'' 43, no. 2 (2011): 178–200.&lt;/ref&gt; on the site.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/TeHEP_SEASON_FIVE_2010_REPORT.pdf |format=PDF |title=TeHEP Season Five 2010 Report |publisher=tallelhammam.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last=Bolen |first=Todd |title=Arguments Against Locating Sodom at Tall el-Hammam |publisher=[[Biblical Archaeology Society]] |date=2013-02-27 |url= http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/biblical-sites-places/biblical-archaeology-sites/arguments-against-locating-sodom-at-tall-el-hammam/ |accessdate=3 July 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Professor [[Eugene H. Merrill (academic)|Eugene H. Merrill]] believes that the identification of Tall el-Hammeh with Sodom would require an unacceptable restructuring of the biblical chronology.&lt;ref&gt;Merrill, Eugene H. "Texts, Talls, and Old Testament Chronology: Tall Hammam as a Case Study." ''Artifax'' 27, no. 4 (2012): 20–21.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last=Bolen |first=Todd |title=Arguments Against Locating Sodom at Tall el-Hammam |url= http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/biblical-sites-places/biblical-archaeology-sites/arguments-against-locating-sodom-at-tall-el-hammam/ |publisher=Biblical Archaeology Society |accessdate=3 July 2013 |date=2013-02-27}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Contra Collins, Steven. "[http://www.tallelhammam.com/uploads/BRB-2013-1-Collins_Answers_Merrill.pdf Tall el-Hammam Is Still Sodom: Critical Data-Sets Cast Serious Doubt on E. H. Merrill’s Chronological Analysis.]" (PDF) ''Biblical Research Bulletin'' 13, no. 1 (2013): 1–31.&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
</tr>
